  "prompt": "Is Blender a viable way to make 2D games for a mobile platform?",
  "response": "Blender is primarily a 3D modeling, animation, and rendering software, but it can be used for 2D game development with some limitations:\n\nPros:\n- Free and open-source\n- Built-in game engine (Blender Game Engine, though it's being phased out)\n- Can create 2D sprites and animations\n- Supports scripting with Python\n\nCons:\n- Not specifically designed for 2D game development\n- Limited 2D-specific tools compared to dedicated 2D game engines\n- Export to mobile platforms can be challenging\n- Performance may not be optimal\n\nBetter alternatives for 2D mobile game development:\n1. Unity (cross-platform, supports 2D)\n2. Godot (free, open-source, excellent 2D support)\n3. GameMaker Studio\n4. Construct\n5. Cocos2d\n\nIf you're committed to Blender, you might want to:\n- Use Blender for asset creation\n- Export assets to a more mobile-friendly game engine\n- Use a game engine with better mobile support for actual development\n\nRecommendation: For mobile 2D game development, use a dedicated game engine like Unity or Godot.",
